======================================================================
PART 6: Why 4-reversal is trivial at n=5
======================================================================
  WHY 4-reversal is H-preserving at n=5:
    - alpha_2 = 0 always (not enough vertices for disjoint pairs)
    - H = 1 + 2*(c3 + c5)
    - 4-reversal preserves c3 (vertex sets are the same, cycle existence preserved)
    - 4-reversal preserves c5 (reversal maps cycles to reverse cycles)
    - Therefore H is preserved.

  WHY this breaks at n=7:
    - alpha_2 > 0 possible (disjoint 3-cycle pairs exist)
    - H = 1 + 2*(c3+c5+c7) + 4*alpha_2
    - 4-reversal preserves c3 (on vertex sets not wholly in the 4-set)
    - BUT: 5-cycles using MIXED vertices (some in 4-set, some outside)
      can change direction! The reversal of internal arcs can create or
      destroy directed 5-cycles that span the boundary.
    - So c5 (counted over 5-vertex subsets) CAN change.
    - And disjoint pair structure can change too.

